      "content": "Ah, you're onto something with the nutrient theft theory! In the world of gardening, it's not uncommon for certain issues to act like sneaky goblins, stealing nutrients from your plants before they can reach the rest of the garden. Nitrogen deficiency can indeed cause the lower leaves to yellow, as these leaves are the first to suffer when the plant is in need of more nutrients. To determine if it's a deficiency or a soil blockage, you might want to take a closer look at your soil. Is it compacted, or is there a buildup of clay? These factors can prevent nutrients from reaching the roots. You could also try a simple soil test kit to check the pH and nutrient levels. If the soil is too acidic or alkaline, it can affect nutrient availability. Remember, a happy soil is a happy plant, and keeping an eye on it can help prevent those sneaky goblins from causing too much trouble. Happy gardening!",
